INTRODUCTION This instrument, known traditionally as the clrsach in Scotland or clirseach in Ireland, is not merely a musical tool but a profound cultural artifact, emblematic of Gaelic heritage. Its unique sonic qualities and historical significance are a direct result of its specific design and material composition.
WHY CELTIC HARP? Through this project, we will be able to gain experience in the following:- The frame of a harp is under constant, immense tension from the strings. We will have to perform stress and strain analysis on the frame (pillar, neck, and body) to prevent it from warping or breaking. The heart of the harp is its soundboard. We will learn the fundamentals of acoustics and how sound is engineered in such instruments This project gives us exposure to understand multifaceted principles of manufacturing such as advanced woodworking techniques, material selections, and joining techniques. Most importantly, the end result of this project is a beautiful Celtic Harp which is a strong motivation itself.

NECK 6 Neck of the Celtic Harp hosts the tuning pegs through which the strings are connected to the soundboard. Neck Tuning Peg
PILLAR/FRAME 7 The Pillar or the Frame of the Celtic Harp is a link between the Neck and the Soundbox joined at the base. Pillar
SOUNDBOX 8 The soundboard of a Celtic harp is a thin, resonant wooden plate, often made from spruce or a plywood laminate, that forms the top surface of the harp's body. Its primary functions are to absorb the tension of the strings, transfer their vibrations to the harp's soundbox, and project the resulting sound, thereby defining the instrument's overall tone and quality. Soundbox is a hollow amplification structure to resonate the sound vibrations Soundboard Soundbox Base

MANUFACTURING PARAMETERS Wood Selection and Working Parameters The wood should be carefully selected for its high stiffness- to-mass ratio, as this ensures strong, resonant sound production. Spruce is a preferred choice due to its light weight and excellent vibrational properties. However we will use whatever wood is available. During construction, reinforcement should be kept minimal using thin veneers only where necessary since excessive layering lowers acoustic efficiency and increases damping. Adhesives must be applied in the thinnest possible layer, as glue contributes significantly to internal friction and energy loss. Similarly, varnish or finish should be limited to fine, thin coats that protect the wood without impairing its vibrational response. Finally, the wood should be well-conditioned to stable humidity and temperature to maintain consistent performance and prevent warping or cracking. Credits: https://jwoodscience.springeropen.com/articles/10.1007/s10086-012-1253-y
MANUFACTURING PARAMETERS Strings and Tuning Nylon strings show variation in stiffness across manufacturers, and their Youngs modulus depends on stress and vibration frequency, making tuning less predictable. They undergo creep, slowly elongating under tension, so new strings drift in pitch until they settle. Both temperature and humidity significantly affect their length, stiffness, and density, causing tuning instability. Additionally, stretching changes the strings cross-section and linear density, further influencing pitch. A lot of tuning pegs are available and the choice will be made based on availability and feasibility. We will try to manufacture our own tuning pegs using some harder wood but in the case of failure, we shall resort to using market-bought tuning pegs.
